{"title_page": "Prince Leopold of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|prince\n| name         = Prince Leopold\n| title        = Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha<br>Duke of Saxony\n| image        = Leopoldkoh\u00e1ry.jpg\n| caption      =\n| spouse       = [[Constanze Geiger]]\n| issue        = [[Franz, Baron of Ruttenstein]]\n| full name    = Leopold Franz Julius\n| house        = [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| father       = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n| mother       = [[Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1824|1|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Vienna]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1884|5|20|1824|1|31|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Vienna]]\n| burial_place = ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Friedhof am Glockenberg|de}}'', Coburg\n| religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n|}}\n'''Prince Leopold Franz Julius of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha''' ([[Vienna]], 31 January 1824 &ndash; [[Vienna]], 20 May 1884) was a German prince of the [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]].\n\nBorn ''Prince Leopold Franz Julius of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, Duke in Saxony'', he was the third son of [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]] and [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]].\n\nLeopold was a younger son and was unlikely to inherit titles or land, so he entered the Army in the service of the Austrian Empire. At one point Leopold was considered as a potential husband for [[Isabel II of Spain]]. This did not, however, prove to be realistic, given the resistance of [[France]] and other European powers. [[Spain]] had been the scene of Great Power rivalry throughout the period since 1815 and all the Great Powers were seeking to exert their influence by supporting different candidates. The [[Saxe-Coburg]] family was perceived to be too closely linked with British interests. The [[Coburg]] influence extended widely. In [[Great Britain]], [[Queen Victoria]] and her husband [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] were Leopold's first cousins, while [[Leopold I of Belgium]] was Leopold's paternal and [[Queen Victoria]]'s maternal uncle, and Leopold's brother was King [[Ferdinand II of Portugal]], husband of Queen [[Maria II of Portugal]].  Leopold's candidature in the affair of the Spanish Marriages was used by [[France]] as the excuse to negotiate the hasty marriage between Queen [[Isabella II of Spain]] and her cousin [[Francis of Spain]], at the same time as that between the son of [[Louis Philippe]] and the Queen of Spain's younger sister.<ref>Kenneth Bourne, The Foreign Policy of Victorian England 1830-1902 (Oxford, 1970), pp.58-60</ref>\n\nLater, Leopold met [[Constanze Geiger]], a common woman. She bore him a son, called [[Franz, Baron of Ruttenstein|Franz]] in [[Vienna]] on 12 October 1860. Leopold and Constanze married six months later, on 23 April 1861. Immediately, he recognized his son, who was created ''Freiherr von Ruttenstein'' on 24 July 1862. The same day, Constanze was created ''Freifrau von Ruttenstein'' in her own right. Because the marriage of his parents was unequal (and thus [[morganatic]]), Franz was barred from the succession of Koh\u00e1ry and Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. Regardless, he died childless and unmarried on 29 August 1899.\n\nLeopold is buried in the ducal mausoleum at ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Friedhof am Glockenberg|de}}'', Coburg.<ref name=\"Guide\">{{cite book|last=Kl\u00fcglein|first=Norbert|title=Coburg Stadt und Land (German)|publisher=Verkehrsverein Coburg|year=1991|isbn=| page=}}</ref>{{rp|47}}\n\n== Honours ==\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Royal Order of Leopold]], ''1850''<ref>Le livre d'or de l'ordre de L\u00e9opold et de la croix de fer, Volume 1 /Ferdinand Veldekens</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Altenburg}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Meiningen}} [[Ernestine duchies]]: Grand Cross of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], ''March 1842''<ref name = \"Handbuch02\">''Adre\u00df-Handbuch des Herzogthums Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'' (1843). \"Herzoglich Sachsen-Ernestinischer Hausorden\", [https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00243961/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_165771801_1843_0040.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00473415 p. 3]</ref>\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], ''19 June 1843''<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de|last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9-10 |issue= |page=9 |doi= ||access-date=28 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*E. Jones-Parry, The Spanish Marriages, 1841-1846 (London, 1936)\n\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld}}\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leopold Of Saxe-Coburg-Kohary, Prince}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n[[Category:House of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Ducal Family Mausoleum, Glockenburg Cemetery, Coburg]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Saxe-Ernestine House Order]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|prince\n| name         = Prince Leopold\n| title        = Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha<br>Duke of Saxony\n| image        = Leopoldkoh\u00e1ry.jpg\n| caption      =\n| spouse       = [[Constanze Geiger]]\n| issue        = [[Franz, Baron of Ruttenstein]]\n| full name    = Leopold Franz Julius\n| house        = [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| father       = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n| mother       = [[Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1824|1|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Vienna]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1884|5|20|1824|1|31|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Vienna]]\n| burial_place = ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Friedhof am Glockenberg|de}}'', Coburg\n| religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n|}}\n'''Prince Leopold Franz Julius of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha''' ([[Vienna]], 31 January 1824 &ndash; [[Vienna]], 20 May 1884) was a German prince of the [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]].\n\nBorn ''Prince Leopold Franz Julius of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, Duke in Saxony'', he was the third son of [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]] and Princess [[Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]].\n\nLeopold was a younger son and was unlikely to inherit titles or land, so he entered the Army in the service of the Austrian Empire. At one point Leopold was considered as a potential husband for [[Isabel II of Spain]]. This did not, however, prove to be realistic, given the resistance of [[France]] and other European powers. [[Spain]] had been the scene of Great Power rivalry throughout the period since 1815 and all the Great Powers were seeking to exert their influence by supporting different candidates. The [[Saxe-Coburg]] family was perceived to be too closely linked with British interests. The [[Coburg]] influence extended widely. In [[Great Britain]], [[Queen Victoria]] and her husband [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] were Leopold's first cousins, while [[Leopold I of Belgium]] was Leopold's paternal and [[Queen Victoria]]'s maternal uncle, and Leopold's brother was King [[Ferdinand II of Portugal]], husband of Queen [[Maria II of Portugal]].  Leopold's candidature in the affair of the Spanish Marriages was used by [[France]] as the excuse to negotiate the hasty marriage between Queen [[Isabella II of Spain]] and her cousin [[Francis of Spain]], at the same time as that between the son of [[Louis Philippe]] and the Queen of Spain's younger sister.<ref>Kenneth Bourne, The Foreign Policy of Victorian England 1830-1902 (Oxford, 1970), pp.58-60</ref>\n\nLater, Leopold met [[Constanze Geiger]], a common woman. She bore him a son, called [[Franz, Baron of Ruttenstein|Franz]] in [[Vienna]] on 12 October 1860. Leopold and Constanze married six months later, on 23 April 1861. Immediately, he recognized his son, who was created ''Freiherr von Ruttenstein'' on 24 July 1862. The same day, Constanze was created ''Freifrau von Ruttenstein'' in her own right. Because the marriage of his parents was unequal (and thus [[morganatic]]), Franz was barred from the succession of Koh\u00e1ry and Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. Regardless, he died childless and unmarried on 29 August 1899.\n\nLeopold is buried in the ducal mausoleum at ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Friedhof am Glockenberg|de}}'', Coburg.<ref name=\"Guide\">{{cite book|last=Kl\u00fcglein|first=Norbert|title=Coburg Stadt und Land (German)|publisher=Verkehrsverein Coburg|year=1991|isbn=| page=}}</ref>{{rp|47}}\n\n== Honours ==\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Royal Order of Leopold]], ''1850''<ref>Le livre d'or de l'ordre de L\u00e9opold et de la croix de fer, Volume 1 /Ferdinand Veldekens</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Altenburg}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Meiningen}} [[Ernestine duchies]]: Grand Cross of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], ''March 1842''<ref name = \"Handbuch02\">''Adre\u00df-Handbuch des Herzogthums Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'' (1843). \"Herzoglich Sachsen-Ernestinischer Hausorden\", [https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00243961/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_165771801_1843_0040.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00473415 p. 3]</ref>\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Portugal}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], ''19 June 1843''<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de|last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9-10 |issue= |page=9 |doi= ||access-date=28 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*E. Jones-Parry, The Spanish Marriages, 1841-1846 (London, 1936)\n\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld}}\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leopold Of Saxe-Coburg-Kohary, Prince}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n[[Category:House of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Ducal Family Mausoleum, Glockenburg Cemetery, Coburg]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Saxe-Ernestine House Order]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "use same link throughout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_Leopold_of_Saxe-Coburg_and_Gotha"}
{"title_page": "Winter solstice", "text_new": "{{about|the astronomical phenomenon}}\n{{redirect|Midwinter}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n| holiday_name=Winter solstice\n| image=LHS sunstones.jpg\n| caption=[[Lawrence Hall of Science]] visitors observe sunset on the day of the winter solstice using the Sunstones II.\n| observedby=Various cultures\n| date=about December 21 ([[Northern Hemisphere|NH]])<br />about June 21 ([[Southern Hemisphere|SH]])\n| celebrations=Festivals, spending time with loved ones, feasting, singing, dancing, fires\n| type=Cultural, astronomical\n| significance=Astronomically marks the beginning of lengthening days and shortening nights\n| relatedto=[[List of winter festivals|Winter festivals]] and the [[solstice]]\n| nickname=Midwinter, [[Yule]], the Longest Night, J\u00f3l\n| duration=1 day\n| frequency=Twice a year (once in the northern hemisphere, once in the southern hemisphere, six months apart)\n}}\n\nThe '''winter solstice''', '''hiemal solstice''' or '''hibernal solstice''', also known as '''midwinter''', occurs when one of the Earth's poles has its maximum tilt away from the Sun. It happens twice yearly, once in each hemisphere (Northern and Southern). For that hemisphere, the winter solstice is the day with the shortest period of daylight and longest night of the year, when the Sun is at its lowest [[Culmination|daily maximum elevation]] in the sky.<ref>{{cite book |title=An Introduction to Physical Science |edition=12th |first1=James |last1=Shipman |first2=Jerry D. |last2=Wilson |first3=Aaron |last3=Todd |chapter=Section 15.5 |page=423 |isbn=978-0-618-92696-1 |year=2007 |location=Boston|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]]}}</ref> At the pole, there is [[Polar night|continuous darkness or twilight]] around the winter solstice. Its opposite is the [[summer solstice]].\n\n\n\nThe winter solstice occurs during the hemisphere's [[winter]]. In the [[Northern Hemisphere]], this is the [[December solstice]] (usually 21 or 22 December) and in the [[Southern Hemisphere]], this is the [[June solstice]] (usually 20 or 21 June). Although the winter solstice itself lasts only a moment, the term sometimes refers to the day on which it occurs. Other names are \"midwinter\", the \"extreme of winter\" ([[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]), or the \"shortest day\". Traditionally, in many [[Temperate climate|temperate]] regions, the winter solstice is seen as the middle of winter, but today in some countries and calendars, it is seen as the beginning of winter. In [[meteorology]], winter is reckoned as beginning about three weeks before the winter solstice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/learning/learn-about-the-weather/how-weather-works/when-does-spring-start|title=When does spring start?|date=June 3, 2016 |accessdate=December 22, 2016 |publisher=[[Met Office]]}}</ref>\n\nSince prehistory, the winter solstice has been seen as a significant time of year in many cultures, and has been marked by festivals and rituals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/winter_solstice.htm|title=Winter Solstice celebrations: a.k.a. Christmas, Saturnalia, Yule, the Long Night, start of Winter, etc.|last=|first=|date=August 5, 2015 |origyear=December 3, 1999|website=|publisher=Religious Tolerance.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It marked the symbolic death and rebirth of the Sun.<ref>Krupp, E C. ''Echoes of the Ancient Skies: The Astronomy of Lost Civilizations''. Courier Corporation, 2012. pp.119, 125, 195</ref><ref>North, John. ''Stonehenge''. The Free Press, 1996. p.530</ref><ref>Hadingham, Evan. ''Early Man and the Cosmos''. University of Oklahoma Press, 1985. p.50</ref> The seasonal significance of the winter solstice is in the reversal of the gradual lengthening of nights and shortening of days...\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== History and cultural significance ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Amaterasu cave - large - 1856.jpeg|thumb|Japanese Sun goddess [[Amaterasu]] emerging from a cave (by [[Kunisada]])]]\n[[File:Seasonearth.png|thumb|Winter solstice occurs in December for the northern hemisphere, and June for the southern hemisphere.]]\n\nThe [[solstice]] may have been a special moment of the annual cycle for some cultures even during [[neolithic]] times. Astronomical events were often used to guide activities, such as the [[mating of animals]], the sowing of crops and the monitoring of winter reserves of food. Many cultural mythologies and traditions are derived from this.\n\nThis is attested by physical remains in the layouts of late Neolithic and [[Bronze Age]] archaeological sites, such as [[Stonehenge]] in England and [[Newgrange]] in Ireland. The primary [[wikt:axis|axes]] of both of these monuments seem to have been carefully aligned on a sight-line pointing to the winter solstice sunrise (Newgrange) and the winter solstice sunset (Stonehenge). It is significant that at Stonehenge the Great [[Trilithon]] was oriented outwards from the middle of the monument, i.e. its smooth flat face was turned towards the midwinter Sun.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Johnson |first1=Anthony |title=Solving Stonehenge: The New Key to an Ancient Enigma |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |year=2008 |isbn=9780500051559 |pages=252\u2013253}}</ref>\n\nThe winter solstice was immensely important because the people were economically dependent on monitoring the progress of the seasons. [[Starvation]] was common during the first months of the winter, January to April (northern hemisphere) or July to October (southern hemisphere), also known as \"the [[famine]] months\". In temperate climates, the midwinter festival was the last feast [[Festival|celebration]], before deep winter began. Most cattle were [[Animal slaughter|slaughter]]ed so they would not have to be fed during the winter, so it was almost the only time of year when a plentiful supply of fresh meat was available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/topics/christmas/history-of-christmas | title=History of Christmas |publisher=History.com |accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> The majority of wine and beer made during the year was finally [[Fermentation (food)|fermented]] and ready for drinking at this time. The concentration of the observances were not always on the day commencing at midnight or at dawn, but at the beginning of the pagan day, which in many cultures fell on the previous [[evening|eve]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nBecause the event was seen as the reversal of the Sun's ebbing presence in the sky, concepts of the birth or rebirth of [[sun god]]s have been common. {{Citation needed|date=February  2020}} In cultures which used cyclic calendars based on the winter solstice, the \"year as reborn\" was celebrated with reference to [[Life-death-rebirth deity|life-death-rebirth deities]] or \"new beginnings\" such as [[Hogmanay]]'s ''redding'', a [[New Year]] cleaning tradition. {{Citation needed|date=February  2020}} Also \"reversal\" is yet another frequent theme, as in [[Saturnalia]]'s slave and master reversals.\n\n===Indian===\n{{main| Makar Sankranti}}\nMakara Sankranti, also known as Makaraa Sankr\u0101nti ([[Sanskrit]]: \u092e\u0915\u0930 \u0938\u0902\u0915\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0902\u0924\u093f) or Maghi, is a festival day in the [[Hindu calendar]], in reference to deity [[Surya]] (sun). It is observed each year in January.<ref name=\"Tumuluru2015p30\"/> It marks the first day of Sun's transit into [[Capricorn (astrology)|Makara (Capricorn)]], marking the end of the month with the winter solstice and the start of longer days.<ref name=\"Tumuluru2015p30\">{{cite book|author=Kamal Kumar Tumuluru|title=Hindu Prayers, Gods and Festivals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b2iyCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT30 |year=2015|publisher=Partridge|isbn=978-1-4828-4707-9|page=30}}</ref><ref name=\"Lochtefeld2002p411\">{{cite book|author=James G. Lochtefeld|title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: A - M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNzLMgEACAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-2287-1|page=411}}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n{{main|Yald\u0101 Night}}\nIranian people celebrate the night of the Northern Hemisphere's winter solstice as, \"[[Yald\u0101 Night|Yalda night]]\", which is known to be the \"longest and darkest night of the year\". [[Yald\u0101 Night|Yalda night]] celebration, or as some call it \"Shabe Chelleh\" (\"the 40th night\"), is one the oldest Iranian traditions that has been present in Persian culture from the ancient years. In this night all the family gather together, usually at the house of the eldest, and celebrate it by eating, drinking and reciting poetry (esp. Hafez). Nuts, pomegranates and watermelons are particularly served during this festival.\n\n===Germanic===\n{{main|Yule}}\nThe [[Norse paganism|pagan Scandinavian]] and [[Germanic people]] of northern Europe celebrated a winter holiday called [[Yule]] (also called Jul, Julblot, j\u00f3labl\u00f3t). The ''[[Heimskringla]]'', written in the 13th century by the Icelander [[Snorri Sturluson]], describes a Yule feast hosted by the Norwegian king [[Haakon the Good]] (c. 920\u2013961). According to Snorri, the Christian Haakon had moved Yule from \"midwinter\" and aligned it with the Christian Christmas celebration. Historically, this has made some scholars believe that Yule originally was a sun festival on the winter solstice. Modern scholars generally do not believe this, as midwinter in medieval Iceland was a date about four weeks after the solstice.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nordberg |first=Andreas |year=2006 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1366945/Jul_disting_och_f%C3%B6rkyrklig_tider%C3%A4kning |title=Jul, disting och f\u00f6rkyrklig tider\u00e4kning: Kalendrar och kalendariska riter i det f\u00f6rkristna Norden |series=Acta Academiae Regiae Gustavi Adolphi |language=Swedish |volume=91 |publisher=Kungl. Gustav Adolfs Akademien f\u00f6r svensk folkkultur |pp=120\u2013121 |isbn=91-85352-62-4 |issn=0065-0897 }}</ref>\n\n===Roman cult of Sol===\n{{main|Dies Natalis Solis Invicti}}\n[[Sol Invictus]] (\"The Unconquered Sun/Invincible Sun\") was originally a Syrian god who was later adopted as the chief god of the [[Roman Empire]] under [[Aurelian|Emperor Aurelian]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Die r\u00f6mischen Kaiser : 55 historische Portraits von Caesar bis Iustinian|last=Clauss|first=Manfred|publisher=Beck|year=2001|isbn=978-3-406-47288-6|location=M\u00fcnchen|pages=250|language=de}}</ref> His holiday is traditionally celebrated on December 25, as are several gods associated with the winter solstice in many pagan traditions.<ref name=Capoccia>{{cite web | last =Capoccia | first =Kathryn  | title =Christmas Traditions | year =2002 | url =http://www.biblebb.com/files/christmas00.htm | accessdate =2008-12-27 }}</ref> It has been speculated to be the reason behind [[Christmas]]' proximity to the solstice.<ref name=\"MacMullen1997\">Bishop Jacob Bar-Salabi (cited in ''Christianity and Paganism in the Fourth to Eighth Centuries'', [[Ramsay MacMullen]]. Yale:1997, p. 155)</ref>\n\n===East Asian===\n{{main|Dongzhi (solar term)}}\nIn [[East Asia]], the winter solstice has been celebrated as one of the [[Solar term|Twenty-four Solar Terms]], called ''[[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]'' in [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. In [[Japan]], in order not to catch [[Common cold|cold]] in the winter, there is a custom to soak oneself in a [[yuzu]] hot bath ({{Lang-ja|\u67da\u5b50\u6e6f}} = Yuzuyu).<ref>[http://goinjapanesque.com/06216/ Goin\u2019 Japanesque!: Japanese Winter Solstice Traditions; A Day for Kabocha and Yuzuyu]</ref> In India, this occasion, known as Ayan Parivartan (Sanskrit: \u0905\u092f\u0928 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924\u0928), is celebrated by religious Hindus as a holy day, with Hindus performing customs such as bathing in holy rivers, giving alms and donations, and praying to God and doing other holy deeds.\n\n== Observations ==\nAlthough the instant of the solstice can be calculated,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Meeus|first1=Jean|title=Astronomical Algorithms|date=2009|publisher=Willmann-Bell, Inc.|location=Richmond, Virginia|isbn=978-0-943396-61-3|edition=2nd English Edition with corrections as of August 10, 2009}}</ref> direct observation of the solstice by amateurs is impossible because the sun moves too slowly or appears to stand still (the meaning of \"solstice\"). However, by use of [[astronomy|astronomical data tracking]], the precise timing of its occurrence is now public knowledge. One cannot directly detect the precise instant of the solstice (by definition, one cannot observe that an object has stopped moving until one later observes that it has not moved further from the preceding spot, or that it has moved in the opposite direction){{Citation needed|reason=Dubious scientific claim for event on a macro scale.|date=December 2014}}. Further, to be precise to a single day, one must be able to observe a change in [[azimuth]] or elevation less than or equal to about 1/60 of the angular diameter of the Sun. Observing that it occurred within a two-day period is easier, requiring an observation precision of only about 1/16 of the angular diameter of the Sun. Thus, many observations are of the day of the solstice rather than the instant. This is often done by observing sunrise and sunset or using an [[Archaeoastronomy|astronomically aligned instrument]] that allows a ray of light to be cast on a certain point around that time. The earliest sunset and latest sunrise dates differ from winter solstice, however, and these depend on latitude, due to the variation in the solar day throughout the year caused by the Earth's elliptical orbit (see [[Analemma#Earliest and latest sunrise and sunset|earliest and latest sunrise and sunset]]).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"\" widths=\"220px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Goseck-2.jpg|[[Neolithic]] site of [[Goseck circle]]. The yellow lines indicate the directions in which sunrise and sunset are seen on the day of the winter solstice.\nFile:StonehengeSunrise1980s.jpg|[[Sunrise]] at [[Stonehenge]] on the winter solstice\n</gallery>\n\n==Holidays celebrated on the winter solstice==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Alban Arthan]] ([[Welsh people|Welsh]])\n*[[Blue Christmas (holiday)]] ([[Western Christian]])\n*[[Brumalia]] ([[Ancient Rome]])\n*[[Dongzhi Festival]] ([[East Asia]])\n*[[Korochun]] ([[Slavic people|Slavic]])\n*[[Sangamitta|Sanghamitta Day]] ([[Theravada|Theravada Buddhism]])\n*[[Shalako]] ([[Zuni people|Zuni]])\n*[[Yald\u0101]] ([[Iran]])\n*[[Yule]] in the Northern Hemisphere ([[Contemporary Paganism|Neopagan]])\n*[[Ziemassv\u0113tki]] (ancient [[Latvia]])\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other related festivals===\n* [[Saturnalia]] ([[Ancient Rome]]): Celebrated shortly before winter solstice\n* [[Saint Lucy's Day]] ([[Christianity|Christian]]): Used to coincide with the winter solstice day\n* [[Christmas]]: Takes place shortly after winter solstice, absorbed tradition from winter solstice celebration. Speculated to originate from solstice date, see [[Christmas#Solstice date]] and [[Dies Natalis Solis Invicti]]\n* [[Cold Food Festival]] ([[Korea]], [[Greater China]]): 105 days after winter solstice\n* [[Makar Sankranti]] / [[Pongal_(festival)|Pongal]] ([[India]]): Harvest Festival - Marks the end of the cold months and start of the new Month with longer days.\n\n==Length of the day near the northern winter solstice==\n{{December solstice}}\nLength of day increases from the equator towards the South Pole in the Southern Hemisphere in December (around the summer solstice there), but decreases towards the North Pole in the Northern Hemisphere at the time of the northern winter solstice.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Holidays}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]\n* [[Burning the Clocks]]\n* [[Christmas in July]]\n* [[December solstice]]\n* [[Effect of sun angle on climate]]\n* [[Equinox]]\n* [[Festival of Lights (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Festive ecology]]\n* [[Festivus]]\n* [[Alcyone|Halcyon days]]\n* [[Hanukkah]]\n* [[HumanLight]]\n* [[June solstice]]\n* [[Koliada]]\n* [[Kwanzaa]]\n* [[Lohri]]\n* [[Makar Sankranti]]\n* [[Midsummer]]\n* [[Summer solstice]]\n* [[Thai Pongal]]\n* [[Tekufah]] \n* [[Tireg\u0101n]]\n* [[Yald\u0101 Night]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | last=Macphail | first=Cameron | title=Winter solstice 2015: Everything you need to know about the shortest day of the year | website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=20 December 2015 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/12058397/When-is-the-winter-solstice-2015-the-shortest-day-of-the-year.html | ref=harv | accessdate=20 December 2015}}\n* {{Cite web|url = http://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/12/151221-winter-solstice-explained-pagans|title = Everything You Need to Know About the Winter Solstice|date = 2015-12-21|accessdate = 2015-12-21|work =[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]|last = Handwerk|first = Brian}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Britannica|645665|Winter solstice (astronomy)}}\n* [http://www.neoprogrammics.com/sun/Northern_Winter_Dates_and_Times.html Table of times/dates from 1600\u20132400]\n\n{{Winter solstice}}\n{{Wheel of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winter Solstice}}\n[[Category:Astronomical events]]\n[[Category:December observances]]\n[[Category:June observances]]\n[[Category:International observances]]\n[[Category:Winter festivals|solstice]]\n[[Category:Winter phenomena|solstice]]\n\n[[de:Sonnenwende#Wintersonnenwende]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the astronomical phenomenon}}\n{{redirect|Midwinter}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n| holiday_name=Winter solstice\n| image=LHS sunstones.jpg\n| caption=[[Lawrence Hall of Science]] visitors observe sunset on the day of the winter solstice using the Sunstones II.\n| observedby=Various cultures\n| date=about December 21 ([[Northern Hemisphere|NH]])<br />about June 21 ([[Southern Hemisphere|SH]])\n| celebrations=Festivals, spending time with loved ones, feasting, singing, dancing, fires\n| type=Cultural, astronomical\n| significance=Astronomically marks the beginning of lengthening days and shortening nights\n| relatedto=[[List of winter festivals|Winter festivals]] and the [[solstice]]\n| nickname=Midwinter, [[Yule]], the Longest Night, J\u00f3l\n| duration=1 day\n| frequency=Twice a year (once in the northern hemisphere, once in the southern hemisphere, six months apart)\n}}\n\nThe '''winter solstice''', '''hiemal solstice''' or '''hibernal solstice''', also known as '''midwinter''', occurs when one of the Earth's poles has its maximum tilt away from the Sun. It happens twice yearly, once in each hemisphere (Northern and Southern). For that hemisphere, the winter solstice is the day with the shortest period of daylight and longest night of the year, when the Sun is at its lowest [[Culmination|daily maximum elevation]] in the sky.<ref>{{cite book |title=An Introduction to Physical Science |edition=12th |first1=James |last1=Shipman |first2=Jerry D. |last2=Wilson |first3=Aaron |last3=Todd |chapter=Section 15.5 |page=423 |isbn=978-0-618-92696-1 |year=2007 |location=Boston|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]]}}</ref> At the pole, there is [[Polar night|continuous darkness or twilight]] around the winter solstice. Its opposite is the [[summer solstice]].\n\nThe winter solstice occurs during the hemisphere's [[winter]]. In the [[Northern Hemisphere]], this is the [[December solstice]] (usually 21 or 22 December) and in the [[Southern Hemisphere]], this is the [[June solstice]] (usually 20 or 21 June). Although the winter solstice itself lasts only a moment, the term sometimes refers to the day on which it occurs. Other names are \"midwinter\", the \"extreme of winter\" ([[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]), or the \"shortest day\". Traditionally, in many [[Temperate climate|temperate]] regions, the winter solstice is seen as the middle of winter, but today in some countries and calendars, it is seen as the beginning of winter. In [[meteorology]], winter is reckoned as beginning about three weeks before the winter solstice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/learning/learn-about-the-weather/how-weather-works/when-does-spring-start|title=When does spring start?|date=June 3, 2016 |accessdate=December 22, 2016 |publisher=[[Met Office]]}}</ref>\n\nSince prehistory, the winter solstice has been seen as a significant time of year in many cultures, and has been marked by festivals and rituals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/winter_solstice.htm|title=Winter Solstice celebrations: a.k.a. Christmas, Saturnalia, Yule, the Long Night, start of Winter, etc.|last=|first=|date=August 5, 2015 |origyear=December 3, 1999|website=|publisher=Religious Tolerance.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It marked the symbolic death and rebirth of the Sun.<ref>Krupp, E C. ''Echoes of the Ancient Skies: The Astronomy of Lost Civilizations''. Courier Corporation, 2012. pp.119, 125, 195</ref><ref>North, John. ''Stonehenge''. The Free Press, 1996. p.530</ref><ref>Hadingham, Evan. ''Early Man and the Cosmos''. University of Oklahoma Press, 1985. p.50</ref> The seasonal significance of the winter solstice is in the reversal of the gradual lengthening of nights and shortening of days.\n\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== History and cultural significance ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Amaterasu cave - large - 1856.jpeg|thumb|Japanese Sun goddess [[Amaterasu]] emerging from a cave (by [[Kunisada]])]]\n[[File:Seasonearth.png|thumb|Winter solstice occurs in December for the northern hemisphere, and June for the southern hemisphere.]]\n\nThe [[solstice]] may have been a special moment of the annual cycle for some cultures even during [[neolithic]] times. Astronomical events were often used to guide activities, such as the [[mating of animals]], the sowing of crops and the monitoring of winter reserves of food. Many cultural mythologies and traditions are derived from this.\n\nThis is attested by physical remains in the layouts of late Neolithic and [[Bronze Age]] archaeological sites, such as [[Stonehenge]] in England and [[Newgrange]] in Ireland. The primary [[wikt:axis|axes]] of both of these monuments seem to have been carefully aligned on a sight-line pointing to the winter solstice sunrise (Newgrange) and the winter solstice sunset (Stonehenge). It is significant that at Stonehenge the Great [[Trilithon]] was oriented outwards from the middle of the monument, i.e. its smooth flat face was turned towards the midwinter Sun.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Johnson |first1=Anthony |title=Solving Stonehenge: The New Key to an Ancient Enigma |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |year=2008 |isbn=9780500051559 |pages=252\u2013253}}</ref>\n\nThe winter solstice was immensely important because the people were economically dependent on monitoring the progress of the seasons. [[Starvation]] was common during the first months of the winter, January to April (northern hemisphere) or July to October (southern hemisphere), also known as \"the [[famine]] months\". In temperate climates, the midwinter festival was the last feast [[Festival|celebration]], before deep winter began. Most cattle were [[Animal slaughter|slaughter]]ed so they would not have to be fed during the winter, so it was almost the only time of year when a plentiful supply of fresh meat was available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/topics/christmas/history-of-christmas | title=History of Christmas |publisher=History.com |accessdate=January 2, 2017}}</ref> The majority of wine and beer made during the year was finally [[Fermentation (food)|fermented]] and ready for drinking at this time. The concentration of the observances were not always on the day commencing at midnight or at dawn, but at the beginning of the pagan day, which in many cultures fell on the previous [[evening|eve]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nBecause the event was seen as the reversal of the Sun's ebbing presence in the sky, concepts of the birth or rebirth of [[sun god]]s have been common. {{Citation needed|date=February  2020}} In cultures which used cyclic calendars based on the winter solstice, the \"year as reborn\" was celebrated with reference to [[Life-death-rebirth deity|life-death-rebirth deities]] or \"new beginnings\" such as [[Hogmanay]]'s ''redding'', a [[New Year]] cleaning tradition. {{Citation needed|date=February  2020}} Also \"reversal\" is yet another frequent theme, as in [[Saturnalia]]'s slave and master reversals.\n\n===Indian===\n{{main| Makar Sankranti}}\nMakara Sankranti, also known as Makaraa Sankr\u0101nti ([[Sanskrit]]: \u092e\u0915\u0930 \u0938\u0902\u0915\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0902\u0924\u093f) or Maghi, is a festival day in the [[Hindu calendar]], in reference to deity [[Surya]] (sun). It is observed each year in January.<ref name=\"Tumuluru2015p30\"/> It marks the first day of Sun's transit into [[Capricorn (astrology)|Makara (Capricorn)]], marking the end of the month with the winter solstice and the start of longer days.<ref name=\"Tumuluru2015p30\">{{cite book|author=Kamal Kumar Tumuluru|title=Hindu Prayers, Gods and Festivals|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b2iyCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT30 |year=2015|publisher=Partridge|isbn=978-1-4828-4707-9|page=30}}</ref><ref name=\"Lochtefeld2002p411\">{{cite book|author=James G. Lochtefeld|title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism: A - M|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNzLMgEACAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-2287-1|page=411}}</ref>\n\n===Iranian===\n{{main|Yald\u0101 Night}}\nIranian people celebrate the night of the Northern Hemisphere's winter solstice as, \"[[Yald\u0101 Night|Yalda night]]\", which is known to be the \"longest and darkest night of the year\". [[Yald\u0101 Night|Yalda night]] celebration, or as some call it \"Shabe Chelleh\" (\"the 40th night\"), is one the oldest Iranian traditions that has been present in Persian culture from the ancient years. In this night all the family gather together, usually at the house of the eldest, and celebrate it by eating, drinking and reciting poetry (esp. Hafez). Nuts, pomegranates and watermelons are particularly served during this festival.\n\n===Germanic===\n{{main|Yule}}\nThe [[Norse paganism|pagan Scandinavian]] and [[Germanic people]] of northern Europe celebrated a winter holiday called [[Yule]] (also called Jul, Julblot, j\u00f3labl\u00f3t). The ''[[Heimskringla]]'', written in the 13th century by the Icelander [[Snorri Sturluson]], describes a Yule feast hosted by the Norwegian king [[Haakon the Good]] (c. 920\u2013961). According to Snorri, the Christian Haakon had moved Yule from \"midwinter\" and aligned it with the Christian Christmas celebration. Historically, this has made some scholars believe that Yule originally was a sun festival on the winter solstice. Modern scholars generally do not believe this, as midwinter in medieval Iceland was a date about four weeks after the solstice.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nordberg |first=Andreas |year=2006 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1366945/Jul_disting_och_f%C3%B6rkyrklig_tider%C3%A4kning |title=Jul, disting och f\u00f6rkyrklig tider\u00e4kning: Kalendrar och kalendariska riter i det f\u00f6rkristna Norden |series=Acta Academiae Regiae Gustavi Adolphi |language=Swedish |volume=91 |publisher=Kungl. Gustav Adolfs Akademien f\u00f6r svensk folkkultur |pp=120\u2013121 |isbn=91-85352-62-4 |issn=0065-0897 }}</ref>\n\n===Roman cult of Sol===\n{{main|Dies Natalis Solis Invicti}}\n[[Sol Invictus]] (\"The Unconquered Sun/Invincible Sun\") was originally a Syrian god who was later adopted as the chief god of the [[Roman Empire]] under [[Aurelian|Emperor Aurelian]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Die r\u00f6mischen Kaiser : 55 historische Portraits von Caesar bis Iustinian|last=Clauss|first=Manfred|publisher=Beck|year=2001|isbn=978-3-406-47288-6|location=M\u00fcnchen|pages=250|language=de}}</ref> His holiday is traditionally celebrated on December 25, as are several gods associated with the winter solstice in many pagan traditions.<ref name=Capoccia>{{cite web | last =Capoccia | first =Kathryn  | title =Christmas Traditions | year =2002 | url =http://www.biblebb.com/files/christmas00.htm | accessdate =2008-12-27 }}</ref> It has been speculated to be the reason behind [[Christmas]]' proximity to the solstice.<ref name=\"MacMullen1997\">Bishop Jacob Bar-Salabi (cited in ''Christianity and Paganism in the Fourth to Eighth Centuries'', [[Ramsay MacMullen]]. Yale:1997, p. 155)</ref>\n\n===East Asian===\n{{main|Dongzhi (solar term)}}\nIn [[East Asia]], the winter solstice has been celebrated as one of the [[Solar term|Twenty-four Solar Terms]], called ''[[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]'' in [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. In [[Japan]], in order not to catch [[Common cold|cold]] in the winter, there is a custom to soak oneself in a [[yuzu]] hot bath ({{Lang-ja|\u67da\u5b50\u6e6f}} = Yuzuyu).<ref>[http://goinjapanesque.com/06216/ Goin\u2019 Japanesque!: Japanese Winter Solstice Traditions; A Day for Kabocha and Yuzuyu]</ref> In India, this occasion, known as Ayan Parivartan (Sanskrit: \u0905\u092f\u0928 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924\u0928), is celebrated by religious Hindus as a holy day, with Hindus performing customs such as bathing in holy rivers, giving alms and donations, and praying to God and doing other holy deeds.\n\n== Observations ==\nAlthough the instant of the solstice can be calculated,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Meeus|first1=Jean|title=Astronomical Algorithms|date=2009|publisher=Willmann-Bell, Inc.|location=Richmond, Virginia|isbn=978-0-943396-61-3|edition=2nd English Edition with corrections as of August 10, 2009}}</ref> direct observation of the solstice by amateurs is impossible because the sun moves too slowly or appears to stand still (the meaning of \"solstice\"). However, by use of [[astronomy|astronomical data tracking]], the precise timing of its occurrence is now public knowledge. One cannot directly detect the precise instant of the solstice (by definition, one cannot observe that an object has stopped moving until one later observes that it has not moved further from the preceding spot, or that it has moved in the opposite direction){{Citation needed|reason=Dubious scientific claim for event on a macro scale.|date=December 2014}}. Further, to be precise to a single day, one must be able to observe a change in [[azimuth]] or elevation less than or equal to about 1/60 of the angular diameter of the Sun. Observing that it occurred within a two-day period is easier, requiring an observation precision of only about 1/16 of the angular diameter of the Sun. Thus, many observations are of the day of the solstice rather than the instant. This is often done by observing sunrise and sunset or using an [[Archaeoastronomy|astronomically aligned instrument]] that allows a ray of light to be cast on a certain point around that time. The earliest sunset and latest sunrise dates differ from winter solstice, however, and these depend on latitude, due to the variation in the solar day throughout the year caused by the Earth's elliptical orbit (see [[Analemma#Earliest and latest sunrise and sunset|earliest and latest sunrise and sunset]]).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"\" widths=\"220px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Goseck-2.jpg|[[Neolithic]] site of [[Goseck circle]]. The yellow lines indicate the directions in which sunrise and sunset are seen on the day of the winter solstice.\nFile:StonehengeSunrise1980s.jpg|[[Sunrise]] at [[Stonehenge]] on the winter solstice\n</gallery>\n\n==Holidays celebrated on the winter solstice==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Alban Arthan]] ([[Welsh people|Welsh]])\n*[[Blue Christmas (holiday)]] ([[Western Christian]])\n*[[Brumalia]] ([[Ancient Rome]])\n*[[Dongzhi Festival]] ([[East Asia]])\n*[[Korochun]] ([[Slavic people|Slavic]])\n*[[Sangamitta|Sanghamitta Day]] ([[Theravada|Theravada Buddhism]])\n*[[Shalako]] ([[Zuni people|Zuni]])\n*[[Yald\u0101]] ([[Iran]])\n*[[Yule]] in the Northern Hemisphere ([[Contemporary Paganism|Neopagan]])\n*[[Ziemassv\u0113tki]] (ancient [[Latvia]])\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other related festivals===\n* [[Saturnalia]] ([[Ancient Rome]]): Celebrated shortly before winter solstice\n* [[Saint Lucy's Day]] ([[Christianity|Christian]]): Used to coincide with the winter solstice day\n* [[Christmas]]: Takes place shortly after winter solstice, absorbed tradition from winter solstice celebration. Speculated to originate from solstice date, see [[Christmas#Solstice date]] and [[Dies Natalis Solis Invicti]]\n* [[Cold Food Festival]] ([[Korea]], [[Greater China]]): 105 days after winter solstice\n* [[Makar Sankranti]] / [[Pongal_(festival)|Pongal]] ([[India]]): Harvest Festival - Marks the end of the cold months and start of the new Month with longer days.\n\n==Length of the day near the northern winter solstice==\n{{December solstice}}\nLength of day increases from the equator towards the South Pole in the Southern Hemisphere in December (around the summer solstice there), but decreases towards the North Pole in the Northern Hemisphere at the time of the northern winter solstice.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Holidays}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Dongzhi (solar term)|Dongzhi]]\n* [[Burning the Clocks]]\n* [[Christmas in July]]\n* [[December solstice]]\n* [[Effect of sun angle on climate]]\n* [[Equinox]]\n* [[Festival of Lights (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Festive ecology]]\n* [[Festivus]]\n* [[Alcyone|Halcyon days]]\n* [[Hanukkah]]\n* [[HumanLight]]\n* [[June solstice]]\n* [[Koliada]]\n* [[Kwanzaa]]\n* [[Lohri]]\n* [[Makar Sankranti]]\n* [[Midsummer]]\n* [[Summer solstice]]\n* [[Thai Pongal]]\n* [[Tekufah]] \n* [[Tireg\u0101n]]\n* [[Yald\u0101 Night]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | last=Macphail | first=Cameron | title=Winter solstice 2015: Everything you need to know about the shortest day of the year | website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=20 December 2015 | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/science/12058397/When-is-the-winter-solstice-2015-the-shortest-day-of-the-year.html | ref=harv | accessdate=20 December 2015}}\n* {{Cite web|url = http://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/12/151221-winter-solstice-explained-pagans|title = Everything You Need to Know About the Winter Solstice|date = 2015-12-21|accessdate = 2015-12-21|work =[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]|last = Handwerk|first = Brian}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Britannica|645665|Winter solstice (astronomy)}}\n* [http://www.neoprogrammics.com/sun/Northern_Winter_Dates_and_Times.html Table of times/dates from 1600\u20132400]\n\n{{Winter solstice}}\n{{Wheel of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winter Solstice}}\n[[Category:Astronomical events]]\n[[Category:December observances]]\n[[Category:June observances]]\n[[Category:International observances]]\n[[Category:Winter festivals|solstice]]\n[[Category:Winter phenomena|solstice]]\n\n[[de:Sonnenwende#Wintersonnenwende]]\n", "name_user": "Antosabin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added two full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Winter_solstice"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 21\n|ru_appearances1     =14\n|ru_tries1           =7\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =21\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tauranga)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tauranga)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =8\n|ru_triesA           =7\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =21\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = \n|tries3              = \n|goals3              = \n|fieldgoals3         =\n|points3             = \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = Bay of Plenty\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 1\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League Days===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga made history of sorts by playing in the first ever rugby league game in Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. These effort to grow the game in the area ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 21\n|ru_appearances1     =8\n|ru_tries1           =5\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =15\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tauranga)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = 26\n|ru_appearances2     =\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tauranga)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 29\n|ru_appearancesA     =6\n|ru_triesA           =3\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =9\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = \n|tries3              = \n|goals3              = \n|fieldgoals3         =\n|points3             = \n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = Bay of Plenty\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 1\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League Days===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga made history of sorts by playing in the first ever rugby league game in Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. These effort to grow the game in the area ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "Gang of Pusi i Mezinit", "text_new": "{{ref improve|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox criminal organization\n|name       = Gang of Pusi i Mezinit\n|image      = \n|image_size =   \n|caption    = \n|founded    = 1997\n|founding_location = [[Vlor\u00eb]], [[Albania]]\n|years_active = 1\n|territory  = [[Vlor\u00eb]]\n|ethnicity  = [[Albanian people|Albanian]]s\n|membership = Ferdinand Sali Nanaj (Felja)-'''killed'''<br />Adriatik Shehu-'''killed'''<br />Abaz Xhelo Bara-'''killed'''<br />Roland Komira-'''killed'''<br />Dritan Nanaj-'''killed'''<br />Luan Bedaj-'''killed'''<br />Petrit Madallozi (Titi i Rukies)-'''killed'''<br />Astrit Duraj-'''killed'''<br />Medi Aziz Backa (Bu\u00e7 Backa)-'''killed'''<br />Astrit Selaci (Tit Selaci)-'''killed'''<br />Edmond Pano-'''killed'''<br />Sokol Muka-'''killed'''<br />Kastriot Muka-'''killed'''<br />Petrit Muka-'''killed'''\n|activities = \n|allies     = \n|rivals     = [[Gang of \u00c7ole]]\n}}\n{{Albanian Civil War}}\n'''Gang of Pusi i Mezinit''' ({{sq|Banda e Pusit t\u00eb Mezinit}}) was a criminal group with activities throughout southern Albania. Origin of the members of this band was from across the south of the country. Most of them had been imprisoned during the communist regime for crimes. Called by his nickname \"The strongest of the South\", this band had as main rival [[Coles gang]] led by Zani \u00c7aushi. Banda was the well to Brother ardent supporter of the Democratic Party, and apparently this caused even their elimination.\n==Levan Massacre==\n\nLevan massacre occurred on 28 March 1997, and was the bloodiest clash of the riots of 1997. In this violent crash were killed 24 people, 18 white and 6 Roma. The clash took place between Gang of Pusi i Mezinit and the roma residents of the village of [[Levan, Fier|Levan]] in [[Fier]]. The whole Gang of Pusi i Mezinit was eliminated during the collision. \n\nAccording to the police, gang members had recently escaped from prison and missed out on the opening of the military depots and were short of weapons. They went to Levan to take Kalashnikovs from roma villagers, because they believed the roma had too many. The gang members had been celebrating the release from prison at \u201cKlubi i Ilias\u201d in Fier and after consuming large amounts of alcohol went to a bar in Levan and over drinks demanded from the local roma leader one Kalashnikov for each of their gang members. The roma leader explained that the roma had only one Kalashnikov per person and had turned in all the extras at the police station in Fier. Arguments followed and the gang members shot and killed the roma leader and began shooting other roma customers in the bar. Local Roma villagers quickly surrounded the bar and demanded the gang's surrender. Even though they were drunk and poorly armed, the gang continued shooting from inside until they ran out of ammunition. Only three gang members who were sober enough were able to escape. All the remaining gang members were executed by the roma in fear of revenge.\n\nOnly ten days later, seven young roma were massacred near Tepelena in retaliation by friends of the gang. One month later Levan was attacked with heavy artillery by gangs from Vlora and drive by shootings from the Vlore-Fier road became frequent in Levan. Roma started organizing their own defense, however several roma have left Levan since then and moved to Tirana and Durr\u00ebs.\n\n===Trap charges===\nFormer bodyguard of Sali Berisha, and the organiser of the coup of 14 September 1998, '''Izet Haxhia''' accused '''Agim Shehu''' and the director of the Vlora Police Station during 1997, '''Milto Kordha''' (located in his office illegally Rescue Committee) that have raised the trap band of Vlora: \n''Members of that gang were some of the strongest of those years as Tit Saleci, Felja and members of the Mukaj family in Vlora. Most of them were former prisoners and supported the [[Democratic Party of Albania|Democratic Party]] and had thought that on 28 March 1997, there would be a gathering of the Salvation Committee, and decided to go South and kill all the participants along with Zani \u00c7aushin, their protector. At this moment comes into play Agim Shehu and Milto Kordha. They were the ones who assaulted them, and weren't killed by the Roma.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.zemrashqiptare.net/article/muzike/1011/ Masakra m\u00eb e madhe e vitit 1997, rihapet dosja]\n*Gazeta Tema :[https://web.archive.org/web/20110726132259/http://www.edsh.org/diskutime/viewthread.php?tid=2593 T\u00eb v\u00ebrtetat e vitit 1997]\n*Top Channel :[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=00FX00-dJqw Viti 1997]\n[[Category:Albanian Civil War]]\n[[Category:1997 in Albania]]\n[[Category:Albanian mobsters]]\n[[Category:Albanian Mafia]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Albania]]\n", "text_old": "{{ref improve|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox criminal organization\n|name       = Gang of Pusi i Mezinit\n|image      = \n|image_size =   \n|caption    = \n|founded    = 1997\n|founding_location = [[Vlor\u00eb]], [[Albania]]\n|years_active = 1\n|territory  = [[Vlor\u00eb]]\n|ethnicity  = [[Albanian people|Albanian]]s\n|membership = Ferdinand Sali Nanaj (Felja)-'''killed'''<br />Adriatik Shehu-'''killed'''<br />Abaz Xhelo Bara-'''killed'''<br />Roland Komira-'''killed'''<br />Dritan Nanaj-'''killed'''<br />Luan Bedaj-'''killed'''<br />Petrit Madallozi (Titi i Rukies)-'''killed'''<br />Astrit Duraj-'''killed'''<br />Medi Aziz Backa (Bu\u00e7 Backa)-'''killed'''<br />Astrit Selaci (Tit Selaci)-'''killed'''<br />Edmond Pano-'''killed'''<br />Sokol Muka-'''killed'''<br />Kastriot Muka-'''killed'''<br />Petrit Muka-'''killed'''\n|activities = \n|allies     = \n|rivals     = [[Gang of \u00c7ole]]\n}}\n{{Albanian Civil War}}\n'''Gang of Pusi i Mezinit''' ({{sq|Banda e Pusit t\u00eb Mezinit}}) was a criminal group with activities throughout southern Albania. Origin of the members of this band was from across the south of the country. Most of them had been imprisoned during the communist regime for crimes. Called by his nickname \"The strongest of the South\", this band had as main rival [[Coles gang]] led by Zani \u00c7aushi. Banda was the well to Brother ardent supporter of the Democratic Party, and apparently this caused even their elimination.\n==Levan Massacre==\n\nLevan massacre occurred on 28 March 1997, and was the bloodiest clash of the riots of 1997. In this violent crash were killed 24 people, 18 white and 6 Roma. The clash took place between Gang of Pusi i Mezinit and the roma residents of the village of [[Levan, Fier|Levan]] in [[Fier]]. The whole Gang of Pusi i Mezinit was eliminated during the collision. \n\nAccording to the police, gang members had recently escaped from prison and missed out on the opening of the military depots and were short of weapons. They went to Levan to take Kallashnikovs from roma villagers, because they believed the roma had too many. The gang members had been celebrating the release from prison at \u201cKlubi i Ilias\u201d in Fier and after consuming large amounts of alcohol went to a bar in Levan and over drinks demanded from the local roma leader one Kallashnikov for each of their gang members. The roma leader explained that the roma had only one Kallashnikov per person and had turned in all the extras at the police station in Fier. Arguments followed and the gang members shot and killed the roma leader and began shooting other roma customers in the bar. Local Roma villagers quickly surrounded the bar and demanded the gang's surrender. Even though they were drunk and poorly armed, the gang continued shooting from inside until they ran out of ammunition. Only three gang members who were sober enough were able to escape. All the remaining gang members were executed by the roma in fear of revenge.\n\nOnly ten days later, seven young roma were massacred near Tepelena in retaliation by friends of the gang. One month later Levan was attacked with heavy artillery by gangs from Vlora and drive by shootings from the Vlore-Fier road became frequent in Levan. Roma started organizing their own defense, however several roma have left Levan since then and moved to Tirana and Durr\u00ebs.\n\n===Trap charges===\nFormer bodyguard of Sali Berisha, and the organiser of the coup of 14 September 1998, '''Izet Haxhia''' accused '''Agim Shehu''' and the director of the Vlora Police Station during 1997, '''Milto Kordha''' (located in his office illegally Rescue Committee) that have raised the trap band of Vlora: \n''Members of that gang were some of the strongest of those years as Tit Saleci, Felja and members of the Mukaj family in Vlora. Most of them were former prisoners and supported the [[Democratic Party of Albania|Democratic Party]] and had thought that on 28 March 1997, there would be a gathering of the Salvation Committee, and decided to go South and kill all the participants along with Zani \u00c7aushin, their protector. At this moment comes into play Agim Shehu and Milto Kordha. They were the ones who assaulted them, and weren't killed by the Roma.''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.zemrashqiptare.net/article/muzike/1011/ Masakra m\u00eb e madhe e vitit 1997, rihapet dosja]\n*Gazeta Tema :[https://web.archive.org/web/20110726132259/http://www.edsh.org/diskutime/viewthread.php?tid=2593 T\u00eb v\u00ebrtetat e vitit 1997]\n*Top Channel :[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=00FX00-dJqw Viti 1997]\n[[Category:Albanian Civil War]]\n[[Category:1997 in Albania]]\n[[Category:Albanian mobsters]]\n[[Category:Albanian Mafia]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Albania]]\n", "name_user": "Uziel302", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gang_of_Pusi_i_Mezinit"}
{"title_page": "Prince August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Prince August\n| title        = Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha<br>Duke of Saxony\n| image        = Augusto de Saxe-Coburgo-Gotha.jpg\n| caption      = Prince August\n| succession   = 2nd Head of the House of<br>[[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| reign        = 27 August 1851 \u2013 26 July 1881\n| reign-type   = Tenure\n| predecessor  = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ferdinand]]\n| successor    = [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Philipp]]\n| spouse       = [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]]\n| issue        = [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Philipp]]<br> [[Prince Ludwig August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ludwig August]]<br>[[Princess Clotilde of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Clotilde, Archduchess Joseph Karl of Austria]]<br>  [[Princess Amalie of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]]<br>[[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria]]\n| full name    = August Ludwig Viktor\n| house        = [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| father       = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n| mother       = [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1818|6|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Vienna]], [[Austrian Empire]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1881|7|26|1818|6|13|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal Castle]], [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal]]\n| burial_date  =\n| burial_place = [[St. Augustin, Coburg|St. Augustin Cathedral]], [[Coburg]]\n| religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n'''August Victor Louis of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha''' ({{lang-de|August Viktor Ludwig}}; 13 June 1818 &ndash; 26 July 1881), was a German prince of the [[Catholic]] [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]. He was a [[General Major]] in the army of [[Kingdom of Saxony|Saxony]] and the owner of [[\u010cabra\u010f Castle|\u010c\u00e1br\u00e1\u010f]] and [[Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica|\u0160tiavnica]], both in modern-day [[Slovakia]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn ''Prince August Viktor Ludwig of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld'', he was the second son of [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Saalfeld]]. He was born in Vienna on 13 June 1818 and baptised at St. Stephan Cathedral on the 16th of that month. His godparents were his paternal grandmother, [[Countess Augusta Reuss of Ebersdorf]], his aunts, [[Princess Victoria of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld|Victoria, Duchess of Kent]] and [[Princess Louise of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg (1800\u20131831)|Louise, Duchess of Saxe Coburg]].<ref>http://www.matricula.data.icar-us.eu/php/view2.php?ar_id=3670&be_id=2349&ve_id=726778&count={{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Following the 1826 re-distribution in the [[House of Wettin]] of the [[Ernestine duchies]], his dynastic suffix became \"of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha\". His mother was [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]], the daughter and heiress of [[Ferencz J\u00f3zsef Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g|Ferenc J\u00f3zsef, Prince Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]. When Antonia's father died in 1826, she inherited his estates in Slovakia and Hungary. Prince August was a younger brother of King-Consort [[Ferdinand II of Portugal]], a nephew of [[Leopold I of Belgium]], and a first cousin of Britain's [[Queen Victoria]], and her husband, [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]].\n \nIn [[Saint-Cloud]] on 20 April 1843 August married [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]], daughter of [[Louis Philippe of France|Louis Philippe, King of the French]], and of his wife, Princess [[Maria Amalia of the Two Sicilies]].  The couple lived in [[Palais Coburg]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.burgen-austria.com/Palais.asp?Artikel=Coburg%20Palais |title=Palais Coburg |access-date=9 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307213551/http://www.burgen-austria.com/Palais.asp?Artikel=Coburg%20Palais |archive-date=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  He also owned ''B\u00fcrgla\u00df'' Castle in [[Coburg]].  When his mother died in 1862, he inherited her extensive landholdings in Hungary and became one of the largest landowners in the country.<ref>Friedrich Maximilian Oertel: ''Genealogische Tafeln zur Staatengeschichte des neunzehnten Jahrhunderts'', F.A. Brockhaus, 1857, p. 96</ref> He was an honorary member of the Hungarian Geological Society.<ref>Ferenc von Kubinyi and Imre Vahot: ''Ungarn und Siebenb\u00fcrgen in Bildern'', G. Emich, 1834, S. 31</ref>\n\n[[File:Coburg-St.Augustin.jpg|thumb|left|St. Augustin in [[Coburg]]]]\nPrince August built a Catholic church in Coburg. It was [[consecration|consecrated]] in 1860 and was named [[St. Augustin, Coburg|St. Augustin]]. He was later buried in the crypt below this church, as were his wife, his three sons, his daughter-in-law [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil|Leopoldina]] and her four sons.\n\nAugust was a recipient of the [[Grand Cross]] of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], the Portuguese royal [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], the French [[Legion of Honour]] and the Belgian royal [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]].  Furthermore, he was a knight of honour and devotion in the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].<ref>''Adre\u00dfhandbuch des Herzogthums Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'', Meusel, 1854, p. 18</ref>\n\n== Memorial ==\nIn 1885, the Austrian sculptor [[Viktor Oskar Tilgner|Viktor Tilgner]] was commissioned to create a memorial for the late Prince August. The sculpture still stands on private land in [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal]] owned by the Saxe-Coburg ducal family. The base of the sculpture contains a Latin inscription and a text in French: {{lang|fr|Auguste Louis Victor Duc de Saxe Prince de Saxe Cobourg Gotha. A mon mari bien aim\u00e8. 1843 - 1881. Cl\u00e9mentine.}} (\"August Louis Victor, Duke of Saxony, Prince of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. To my beloved husband.\" &mdash; 1843 is not the year August was born (he was born in 1818), but rather the year he married Cl\u00e9mentine).\n\n== Marriage and issue ==\nIn [[Saint-Cloud]] on 20 April 1843 August married [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]], daughter of [[Louis Philippe of France|Louis Philippe, King of the French]]. They had five children:\n# [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Ferdinand Philipp Maria August Raphael]] (b. Paris, 28 March 1844 - d. Coburg, 3 July 1921).\n# [[Prince Ludwig August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Ludwig August Maria Eudes]] (b. Ch\u00e2teau d'Eu, 8 August 1845 - d. Karlsbad, 14 September 1907), married on 15 December 1864 to [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil]].\n# [[Princess Clotilde of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Marie Adelaide Amalie Clotilde]] (b. Neuilly, 8 July 1846 - d. Alcs\u00fat, Hungary, 3 June 1927), married on 12 May 1864 to [[Archduke Joseph Karl of Austria]].\n# [[Princess Amalie of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Marie Luise Franziska Amalie]] (b. Coburg, 23 October 1848 - d. Schlo\u00df Biederstein, 6 May 1894), married on 20 September 1875 to Maximilian Emanuel, Duke in Bavaria.\n# [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria|Ferdinand Maximilian Karl Leopold Maria]] (b. Vienna, 26 February 1861 - d. Coburg, 10 September 1948), installed as Prince of Bulgaria on 7 July 1887; raised to [[Czar]] of Bulgaria on {{OldStyleDate|22 September|1908|5 October}}.\n\nOn 2 May 1881, Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] bestowed upon August and his descendants the style of ''Hoheit'' (\"[[Highness]]\"), a higher style in Germany than ''Durchlaucht'' (\"[[Serene Highness]]\"), which [[Ernestine duchies|Ernestine]] princes were usually entitled to. The reason for the grant was that eight days later [[Princess St\u00e9phanie of Belgium]] (younger sister of August's daughter-in-law [[Princess Louise of Belgium|Louise]]) was to marry Franz Joseph's son [[Rudolf, Crown Prince of Austria|Crown Prince Rudolf]]; Franz Joseph considered it appropriate that his son's in-laws have a higher rank at the Austrian court.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n== Honours ==\nHe received the following awards:<ref name = \"Handbuch\">''Staatshandbuch f\u00fcr die Herzogth\u00fcmer Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'' (1865). \"Genealogie des Herzogliche Hauses\", [https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00244505/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_170545237_1865_0024.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00483244 p. 11]. Gotha: Thienemann.</ref>\n* {{flag|Austrian Empire}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Golden Fleece]], 1862<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiquesatoz.com/sgfleece/knights5.htm |title=Chevaliers de la Tois\u00f3n d'Or - Knights of the Golden Fleece |last= Boettger|first=T. F.|date=|website=La Confr\u00e9rie Amicale|publisher=|access-date=25 June 2019|quote= }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Royal Order of Leopold]], 1844<ref>Le livre d'or de l'ordre de L\u00e9opold et de la croix de fer, Volume 1 /Ferdinand Veldekens</ref>\n* {{flag|Empire of Brazil}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Southern Cross]]\n* {{flagicon|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Altenburg}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Meiningen}} [[Ernestine duchies]]: Grand Cross of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], February 1836<ref>''[https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00244577/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_165771801_1837_0030.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00473385 Staatshandb\u00fccher f\u00fcr das Herzogtum Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha]'' (1837), \"Herzogliche Sachsen-Ernestinischer Hausorden\" p. 11</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of France (1794\u20131815, 1830\u20131958).svg}} [[July Monarchy|Kingdom of France]]: Grand Cross, [[Legion of Honour]], May 1840<ref>{{cite book| author = M. & B. Wattel | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = Les Grand'Croix de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur de 1805 \u00e0 nos jours. Titulaires fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =   |location= Paris |date = 2009 |publisher= Archives & Culture |at=  |volume=  | pages = | page = 523 | series =  | isbn = 978-2-35077-135-9| ref = M. et B. Wattel}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sovereign Military Order of Malta}}: Bailiff Grand Cross of Honour and Devotion\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Portugal}}: [[Grand Cross]] of the [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], 23 April 1836<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de|last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9-10 |issue= |page=7 |doi= ||access-date=28 November 2019 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Saxony}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Rue Crown]], 1848<ref>''Staatshandbuch f\u00fcr den Freistaat Sachsen (1867)'' (in German), \"K\u00f6nigliche Ritter-Orden\", p. 4</ref>\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]] \n|4= 4. [[Francis, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld]]\n|5= 5. [[Countess Augusta Reuss of Ebersdorf]]\n|6= 6. [[Ferenc J\u00f3zsef, Prince Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]\n|7= 7. [[Countess Maria Antonia von Waldstein-Wartenberg]]\n|8= 8. [[Ernest Frederick, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld]]\n|9= 9. [[Duchess Sophie Antoinette of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|10= 10. [[Heinrich XXIV, Count Reuss of Ebersdorf]]\n|11= 11. [[Countess Karoline Ernestine of Erbach-Sch\u00f6nberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Ign\u00e1c J\u00f3zsef, Count Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]\n|13= 13. Countess Maria Gabriella Cavriani\n|14= 14. Count Georg Christian von Waldstein-Wartenberg\n|15= 15. Countess Elisabeth Ulfeldt\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Prince August, 3rd Prince of Koh\u00e1ry}}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld}}\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:August, Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Golden Fleece]]\n[[Category:House of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n[[Category:Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Saxe-Ernestine House Order]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n[[Category:Grand Croix of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Prince August\n| title        = Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha<br>Duke of Saxony\n| image        = Augusto de Saxe-Coburgo-Gotha.jpg\n| caption      = Prince August\n| succession   = 2nd Head of the House of<br>[[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| reign        = 27 August 1851 \u2013 26 July 1881\n| reign-type   = Tenure\n| predecessor  = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ferdinand]]\n| successor    = [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Philipp]]\n| spouse       = [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]]\n| issue        = [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Philipp]]<br> [[Prince Ludwig August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ludwig August]]<br>[[Princess Clotilde of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Clotilde, Archduchess Joseph Karl of Austria]]<br>  [[Princess Amalie of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]]<br>[[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria]]\n| full name    = August Ludwig Viktor\n| house        = [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| father       = [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n| mother       = [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]]\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1818|6|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Vienna]], [[Austrian Empire]]\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1881|7|26|1818|6|13|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal Castle]], [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal]]\n| burial_date  =\n| burial_place = [[St. Augustin, Coburg|St. Augustin Cathedral]], [[Coburg]]\n| religion     = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n'''August Victor Louis of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha''' ({{lang-de|August Viktor Ludwig}}; 13 June 1818 &ndash; 26 July 1881), was a German prince of the [[Catholic]] [[House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha-Koh\u00e1ry]]. He was a [[General Major]] in the army of [[Kingdom of Saxony|Saxony]] and the owner of [[\u010cabra\u010f Castle|\u010c\u00e1br\u00e1\u010f]] and [[Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica|\u0160tiavnica]], both in modern-day [[Slovakia]].\n\n== Life ==\nBorn ''Prince August Viktor Ludwig of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld'', he was the second son of [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Saalfeld]]. He was born in Vienna on 13 June 1818 and baptised at St. Stephan Cathedral on the 16th of that month. His godparents were his paternal grandmother, [[Countess Augusta Reuss of Ebersdorf]], his aunts, [[Princess Victoria of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld|Victoria, Duchess of Kent]] and [[Princess Louise of Saxe-Gotha-Altenburg (1800\u20131831)|Louise, Duchess of Saxe Coburg]].<ref>http://www.matricula.data.icar-us.eu/php/view2.php?ar_id=3670&be_id=2349&ve_id=726778&count={{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Following the 1826 re-distribution in the [[House of Wettin]] of the [[Ernestine duchies]], his dynastic suffix became \"of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha\". His mother was Princess [[Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry]], the daughter and heiress of [[Ferencz J\u00f3zsef Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g|Ferenc J\u00f3zsef, Prince Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]. When Antonia's father died in 1826, she inherited his estates in Slovakia and Hungary. Prince August was a younger brother of King-Consort [[Ferdinand II of Portugal]], a nephew of [[Leopold I of Belgium]], and a first cousin of Britain's [[Queen Victoria]], and her husband, [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]].\n \nIn [[Saint-Cloud]] on 20 April 1843 August married [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]], daughter of [[Louis Philippe of France|Louis Philippe, King of the French]], and of his wife, Princess [[Maria Amalia of the Two Sicilies]].  The couple lived in [[Palais Coburg]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.burgen-austria.com/Palais.asp?Artikel=Coburg%20Palais |title=Palais Coburg |access-date=9 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307213551/http://www.burgen-austria.com/Palais.asp?Artikel=Coburg%20Palais |archive-date=7 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  He also owned ''B\u00fcrgla\u00df'' Castle in [[Coburg]].  When his mother died in 1862, he inherited her extensive landholdings in Hungary and became one of the largest landowners in the country.<ref>Friedrich Maximilian Oertel: ''Genealogische Tafeln zur Staatengeschichte des neunzehnten Jahrhunderts'', F.A. Brockhaus, 1857, p. 96</ref> He was an honorary member of the Hungarian Geological Society.<ref>Ferenc von Kubinyi and Imre Vahot: ''Ungarn und Siebenb\u00fcrgen in Bildern'', G. Emich, 1834, S. 31</ref>\n\n[[File:Coburg-St.Augustin.jpg|thumb|left|St. Augustin in [[Coburg]]]]\nPrince August built a Catholic church in Coburg. It was [[consecration|consecrated]] in 1860 and was named [[St. Augustin, Coburg|St. Augustin]]. He was later buried in the crypt below this church, as were his wife, his three sons, his daughter-in-law [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil|Leopoldina]] and her four sons.\n\nAugust was a recipient of the [[Grand Cross]] of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], the Portuguese royal [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], the French [[Legion of Honour]] and the Belgian royal [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Order of Leopold]].  Furthermore, he was a knight of honour and devotion in the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].<ref>''Adre\u00dfhandbuch des Herzogthums Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'', Meusel, 1854, p. 18</ref>\n\n== Memorial ==\nIn 1885, the Austrian sculptor [[Viktor Oskar Tilgner|Viktor Tilgner]] was commissioned to create a memorial for the late Prince August. The sculpture still stands on private land in [[Ebenthal, Lower Austria|Ebenthal]] owned by the Saxe-Coburg ducal family. The base of the sculpture contains a Latin inscription and a text in French: {{lang|fr|Auguste Louis Victor Duc de Saxe Prince de Saxe Cobourg Gotha. A mon mari bien aim\u00e8. 1843 - 1881. Cl\u00e9mentine.}} (\"August Louis Victor, Duke of Saxony, Prince of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. To my beloved husband.\" &mdash; 1843 is not the year August was born (he was born in 1818), but rather the year he married Cl\u00e9mentine).\n\n== Marriage and issue ==\nIn [[Saint-Cloud]] on 20 April 1843 August married [[Princess Cl\u00e9mentine of Orl\u00e9ans]], daughter of [[Louis Philippe of France|Louis Philippe, King of the French]]. They had five children:\n# [[Prince Philipp of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Ferdinand Philipp Maria August Raphael]] (b. Paris, 28 March 1844 - d. Coburg, 3 July 1921).\n# [[Prince Ludwig August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Ludwig August Maria Eudes]] (b. Ch\u00e2teau d'Eu, 8 August 1845 - d. Karlsbad, 14 September 1907), married on 15 December 1864 to [[Princess Leopoldina of Brazil]].\n# [[Princess Clotilde of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Marie Adelaide Amalie Clotilde]] (b. Neuilly, 8 July 1846 - d. Alcs\u00fat, Hungary, 3 June 1927), married on 12 May 1864 to [[Archduke Joseph Karl of Austria]].\n# [[Princess Amalie of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Marie Luise Franziska Amalie]] (b. Coburg, 23 October 1848 - d. Schlo\u00df Biederstein, 6 May 1894), married on 20 September 1875 to Maximilian Emanuel, Duke in Bavaria.\n# [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria|Ferdinand Maximilian Karl Leopold Maria]] (b. Vienna, 26 February 1861 - d. Coburg, 10 September 1948), installed as Prince of Bulgaria on 7 July 1887; raised to [[Czar]] of Bulgaria on {{OldStyleDate|22 September|1908|5 October}}.\n\nOn 2 May 1881, Emperor [[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] bestowed upon August and his descendants the style of ''Hoheit'' (\"[[Highness]]\"), a higher style in Germany than ''Durchlaucht'' (\"[[Serene Highness]]\"), which [[Ernestine duchies|Ernestine]] princes were usually entitled to. The reason for the grant was that eight days later [[Princess St\u00e9phanie of Belgium]] (younger sister of August's daughter-in-law [[Princess Louise of Belgium|Louise]]) was to marry Franz Joseph's son [[Rudolf, Crown Prince of Austria|Crown Prince Rudolf]]; Franz Joseph considered it appropriate that his son's in-laws have a higher rank at the Austrian court.{{Citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\n== Honours ==\nHe received the following awards:<ref name = \"Handbuch\">''Staatshandbuch f\u00fcr die Herzogth\u00fcmer Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha'' (1865). \"Genealogie des Herzogliche Hauses\", [https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00244505/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_170545237_1865_0024.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00483244 p. 11]. Gotha: Thienemann.</ref>\n* {{flag|Austrian Empire}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Golden Fleece]], 1862<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antiquesatoz.com/sgfleece/knights5.htm |title=Chevaliers de la Tois\u00f3n d'Or - Knights of the Golden Fleece |last= Boettger|first=T. F.|date=|website=La Confr\u00e9rie Amicale|publisher=|access-date=25 June 2019|quote= }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Belgium}}: Grand Cordon of the [[Order of Leopold (Belgium)|Royal Order of Leopold]], 1844<ref>Le livre d'or de l'ordre de L\u00e9opold et de la croix de fer, Volume 1 /Ferdinand Veldekens</ref>\n* {{flag|Empire of Brazil}}: Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Southern Cross]]\n* {{flagicon|Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Altenburg}} {{flagicon|Saxe-Meiningen}} [[Ernestine duchies]]: Grand Cross of the [[Saxe-Ernestine House Order]], February 1836<ref>''[https://zs.thulb.uni-jena.de/rsc/viewer/jportal_derivate_00244577/Sachsen_Coburg_Gotha_165771801_1837_0030.tif?logicalDiv=jportal_jparticle_00473385 Staatshandb\u00fccher f\u00fcr das Herzogtum Sachsen-Coburg und Gotha]'' (1837), \"Herzogliche Sachsen-Ernestinischer Hausorden\" p. 11</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of France (1794\u20131815, 1830\u20131958).svg}} [[July Monarchy|Kingdom of France]]: Grand Cross, [[Legion of Honour]], May 1840<ref>{{cite book| author = M. & B. Wattel | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = Les Grand'Croix de la L\u00e9gion d'honneur de 1805 \u00e0 nos jours. Titulaires fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =   |location= Paris |date = 2009 |publisher= Archives & Culture |at=  |volume=  | pages = | page = 523 | series =  | isbn = 978-2-35077-135-9| ref = M. et B. Wattel}}</ref>\n* {{flag|Sovereign Military Order of Malta}}: Bailiff Grand Cross of Honour and Devotion\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Portugal}}: [[Grand Cross]] of the [[Order of the Tower and Sword]], 23 April 1836<ref name=\"Agraciamentos\">{{cite journal|last1=Bragan\u00e7a |first1=Jose Vicente de|last2= |first2= |date=2014 |title=Agraciamentos Portugueses Aos Pr\u00edncipes da Casa Saxe-Coburgo-Gota |url=https://www.academia.edu/10576008/AGRACIAMENTOS_PORTUGUESES_AOS_PR%C3%8DNCIPES_DA_CASA_SAXE-COBURGO-GOTA_PORTUGUESE_HONOURS_AWARDED_TO_PRINCES_OF_THE_HOUSE_OF_SAXE-COBURG-GOTHA |language=portuguese|trans-title=Portuguese Honours awarded to Princes of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|journal=Pro Phalaris |volume=9-10 |issue= |page=7 |doi= ||access-date=28 November 2019 }}</ref>\n* {{flag|Kingdom of Saxony}}: Knight of the [[Order of the Rue Crown]], 1848<ref>''Staatshandbuch f\u00fcr den Freistaat Sachsen (1867)'' (in German), \"K\u00f6nigliche Ritter-Orden\", p. 4</ref>\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince August of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Ferdinand of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Maria Antonia Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]] \n|4= 4. [[Francis, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld]]\n|5= 5. [[Countess Augusta Reuss of Ebersdorf]]\n|6= 6. [[Ferenc J\u00f3zsef, Prince Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]\n|7= 7. [[Countess Maria Antonia von Waldstein-Wartenberg]]\n|8= 8. [[Ernest Frederick, Duke of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld]]\n|9= 9. [[Duchess Sophie Antoinette of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]\n|10= 10. [[Heinrich XXIV, Count Reuss of Ebersdorf]]\n|11= 11. [[Countess Karoline Ernestine of Erbach-Sch\u00f6nberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Ign\u00e1c J\u00f3zsef, Count Koh\u00e1ry de Cs\u00e1br\u00e1g et Szitnya]]\n|13= 13. Countess Maria Gabriella Cavriani\n|14= 14. Count Georg Christian von Waldstein-Wartenberg\n|15= 15. Countess Elisabeth Ulfeldt\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Prince August, 3rd Prince of Koh\u00e1ry}}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld}}\n{{Princes of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:August, Prince of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\n[[Category:1818 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:Knights of th